Longevity of Contributions to the Open Source Video Game Modding Community¶

By Davis Cook¶

Definitions and Motivation¶

Within the video game community, mods (shorthand for modifications) are community made patches/changes/extensions to a video game. An example of a video game mod would be a change to the game's code that would add new weapons or armor to a fighting game, or add new levels to a puzzle game. The main distinguishing features of mods are that they are created through programming. For example, community made levels created in a level-editor provided by the game's developers would not be considered a video game mod. As such, since mods are created by programmers (often in conjunction with artists), many mods are part of the open source software community. This is not to say that all mods are made as open source software; there are many examples of closed source video game mods.

Despite open source mods not representing the entirety of the video game modding community, this analysis will be strictly focused on the subset of video game mods that are part of the open source community. Specifically the goal of this analysis is to look at the frequency of contributions over time to open source mods. There are two main components of this goal - the frequency over time of contributions by all authors and the frequency over time of contributions segregated on a per-author basis. This will provide insight into the longevity of open source modding projects and into the duration for which an individual contributor makes contributions to a project.

From this analysis the video game modding (modding is defined as the act of creating mods) community will have a better understanding of the longevity of projects and the issue of burn-out for individual mod contributors.

See (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mod_(video_gaming)) for further reading.

Data Collection Procedures¶

In the open source software community, programmers must collaborate using some form of version control. There are many possible version control tools (git and apache subversion to name two major choices) that each open source software project may choose to use. As such, in data collection it is necessary to be aware of the many different version control tools that each project may use. Additionally, within each version control tool there are many more possible ways for the project to be hosted online in a way that the community can partake in it. Two main examples of hosting services for the git version control tool are Github and Gitlab. For the purposes of this analysis, only projects using the git version control tool that are hosted on Github will be examined. Naturally this raises the question of how may limiting the sample to only Github affect the results of the analysis. This choice could potentially bias the results on the longevity of certain projects because using one hosting platform versus another may give a project either more or less visibility within the community which could result in projects on some hosting platform either being systematically less or more likely to continue being worked on by members of the community. The differences between using different version control tools is less obvious how it may impact results. As such it certainly seems important that follow up analysis be performed that takes into account the large variety of version control tools and hosting platforms that exist. Nonetheless this analysis will proceed with only projects that are hosted on Github and made using the git version control tool.

The next important question is that of how the sample of open source video game mods will be choosen. It would be optimal to make a random sample in order to have the best results but unfortunately in this case a random sample is not feasible given the impossibility of enumerating all video games and then furthermore attempting to enumerate all the mods ever created for those video games. Without random sampling and also without wanting to bias the sample by hand-picking the video game mods, the sample will have to be generated in a procedural manner. For this analysis the procedure used to create the sample is as follows: take the top n most popular video games by player count and then select the most popular mod for each of those video games.

This procedure naturally raises many questions which will be now be addressed below:

  1. If the video game is a competitive multiplayer game then it is by nature of being competitive, not designed to be modded. Some examples of popular competitive multiplayer games would be Dota 2 and Counter Strike: Global Offensive. In these games, any modifications would be discouraged (and often punished) by the developers because modifications would damage the competitive nature of the game. In the case of competitive multiplayer first person shooter games, a modification that would be demmed damaging to the competitive nature of the game would be a modification that gave the player more information about the positions of the enemies or other information that the player would not have in the game as it was provided by the developers. Of course one could argue that if the developers provided more information to the client than they wanted the player to be able to access they were using poor security practices - but that is not the focus of this analysis. Instead the importance of this issue is that for the purposes of this analysis any competitive multiplayer game will be skipped. This is because modifications to these games are not done in good faith and would be considered hacks and not part of the open source modding community that this analysis is for. Specifically this means that for the selection procedure, any time a competitive multiplayer game would be chosen, the next video game that is not a competitive multiplayer game will be chosen instead. Do note that this criteria does not exclude cooperative multiplayer games and games in which multiplayer is not the main focus. See (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheating_in_video_games#Cheating_in_online_games) for further reading about mods in online games. Notice how the page doesn't even refer to mods - it simply calls them cheats!
  2. If the most popular mod for a video game is not open source (as previously identified as a real possibility) then the next most popular mod for that video game that is open source will be chosen. See bullet point (4) for how this is accomplished.
  3. The most popular video games by player count will be chosen by looking at the player count data provided by Steam (Steam is the most common DRM platform for video games and is used by the vast majority of the video-gaming community). Unfortunately due to the nature of Steam being a personal computer only video game platform the console (the xbox, playstation, etc... are consoles) modding community will be excluded. Again this decision could warrant further analysis in the future for examining any differences between the personal computer and console modding communities. Additionally there are some games for the personal computer that are not listed on Steam that will be left out of this analysis (for example Minecraft). For more information about Steam see (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steam_(software))
  4. The most popular mod will be determined by a github search for the name of the video game sorted by most stars (where stars in this case are being used to indicate popularity of a mod). However, just picking the top result for this search could result in a poor sample because some projects that are related to a video game may not actually be a mod for the video game. For example, a top result could be a project designed to clone a video game. This would not be a mod but might show as the top result when searching for that video game. As such, some amount of discretion will have to be exercised when making the sample. In order to preserve the integrity of the sample, any cases in which this happens will be noted.
  5. How does having the project data on Github for some open source video game mod project allow for determining data related to the longevity of the contributions to said project? Github provides the commit history of the project which gives the author and date of each contribution to the project. This is exactly the information we need.

url = "https://steamcharts.com/top/p."

frames = []
# grab the first 4 pages of results (page numbering starts at one)
for i in range(1, 5):
    text = requests.get(url + str(i)).text
    soup = BeautifulSoup(text)
    table = soup.find('table').prettify()
    frame = pd.read_html(table, flavor='bs4')[0]
    frames.append(frame)

    
games = []
for frame in frames:
    # each page in the webpage has 25 results
    for row in frame.itertuples():
        games.append(row[2])
        
for game in games:
    print(game)

# transform the project urls to the api url
mod_api_urls = []
for url in mod_urls:
    api_url = url.replace("https://github.com", "https://api.github.com/repos");
    api_url += "/commits?page=1&per_page=100"
    mod_api_urls.append(api_url)
    print(api_url)
    
def parse_response(response, commits):
    json = response.json()
    for commit in json:
        author = commit['commit']['author']['name']
        time = commit['commit']['author']['date']
        commits.append({
            'author': author,
            'time': time
        })
    
response_map = {}
    
def build_frame(url):
    print ("getting " + url)
    # responses are paginated so we must use a loop to grab all the commits
    # in a repository
    commits = []
    responses = []
    response = requests.get(url,
        headers={
            'Authorization': 'token cf03b7f35424a08f30bfcce1619c9219f4a3942b'
        })
    responses.append(response)
    parse_response(response, commits)
    # only need to do pagination code if the project has more than 100 commits
    if ('last' in response.links):
        last_url = response.links['last']['url']
        # this regex gets the last page number
        page_number = re.search(r'page=(\d+).*$', last_url).group(1)
        for i in range(2, int(page_number) + 1):
            next_url = response.links['next']['url']
            response = requests.get(next_url,
                headers={
                    'Authorization': 'token cf03b7f35424a08f30bfcce1619c9219f4a3942b'
                })
            responses.append(response)
            parse_response(response, commits)
    response_map[url] = {
        'commits': commits,
        'responses': responses
    }
        
        
# due to github api rate limits we can only make 5000 requests per hour
# and at 100 commmits per request this limits us to getting 500,000 commits
# which should be more than enough however since this is a long operation
# this code should really only be executed once which is why it stores
# all of the response data so further processing can be performed as necessary
# in a different code block
for mod_api_url in mod_api_urls:
    build_frame(mod_api_url)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

With the data collection completed, an investigation into the data can begin. A list of questions that this EDA will attempt to answer is below:

  1. How does the size of a project (measured in number of commits) relate to the number of contributors to the project? As a hypothesis it would make sense that projects with larger numbers of contributors would have more commits but there may be outliers in which a project with many commits is made only by a small number of contributors or the opposite. This information may be useful because it could help to establish the notion that growing open source video mods could best be done by getting more developers interested in the projects.
  2. What percentage of the total commits in a project are made by the author with the most commits, the second most commits, etc...? This question will look to see if one or two core authors of a project perform the majority of the work or if the contributions to an open source mod are more evenly split among the contributors. Note that the main reason to use commits as an indication of contributions instead of lines of code is because many activities like installing a new dependency or reformatting may involve changing many many lines of code that would not be representative of the work involved. This can be examined overall accross all projects or in relation to the size of a project.
  3. What is the length of time for which a contributor works on a project? This would be defined as the time difference between the time for which an individual author's first commit appears in the commit history and the time for which an individual's last commit appears in the commit history. This duration can be examined overall for all the projects, on a per project basis, and most interestingly in relation to the number of commits/percentage of project commits made by that author.
  4. Is there some trend or pattern in the length of time that an author will work on a project? Is there some way to predict the time at which an author will stop making new contributions to a project given their previous commit history? This could be examined by making a histogram of commit frequency over time periods and determining of there exists some general shape to that graph that could be used to predict at which point commit frequency would go to zero.

r^2 computation for the dataset with the outlier removed = 0.739082524324
prediction equation is commits_hat = 33.3832651461 * authors + 100.053303704
r^2 computation for the dataset with only projects that have 1000 or less commits = 0.702696966766
prediction equation is commits_hat = 27.5858886969 * authors + 57.127840963

The graph with the outlier removed had an r^2 score of 0.739, meanining that 73.9 percent of the variance in the # of commits can be predicted by the # of authors for a project. For the graph with only projects with a # of commits less than or equal to 1000 the r^2 score is 0.703, meaning that 70.3 percent of the variance in the # of commits can be predited by the # of authors for a project. With r^2 scores around 0.7, there is a clear positive correlation between the two variables. But because 0.7 is still far from 1.0 this means that the number of authors alone is insufficient to completely predict the number of commits on a project.

Nonetheless this analysis confirm the prediction that projects with more authors would certainly have more commits. This does not establish whether having more authors causes more commits or having more commits causes more authors but since authors create commits it seems clear that at least to a degree having more authors would cause more commits to be created. But the opposite idea, where having more commits makes a project more likely to attract new developers cannot be ruled out.

Some intriguing results of this analysis are that according to the graphs, all projects with only 1 author have less than 200 commits, meaning that any project with more than 200 commits would have more than 1 author. This would seem to indicate that at a certain point once a project has had some amount of development put towards it (>= 200 commits) it begins to attract attention from other mod developers in the community who also begin to make contributions towards the project.

Additionally with the prediction equations having coefficients of 33.383 and 27.586 it is clear that on average there seems to be about 30 commits made per author to a project. This information leads nicely into the second question about what the distribution of those commits per author looks like for the projects and if each author makes close to the average number of commits or if there is some other distribution for the relationship between # of commits and author.

The above graphs created to the distribution of number of commits fall into three discintion categories:

  1. right-skewed
  2. bimodal
  3. unimodal

Two good examples right-skewed graphs are the graphs for the https://github.com/crosire/scripthookvdotnet project and the https://github.com/Ofaloaf/postapoc project. In these graphs there are many many authors with a small number of commits and there are a few authors with many, many commits that make up the right tail of the distribution. This type of distribution seems to indicate a project in which there is a small number of core contributors that create the majority of the commits in the project and many additional contributors that each write a few commits each.

An example of a bimodal graph is the graph for the https://github.com/swiftb/clicker-heroes/sw1ft-bit project and the https://github.com/wube/factorio-data project. However calling these graphs bimodal is a bit disingenuous. In reality the reason for these graphs being bimodal is that there are some number of authors with a really small number of commits and one singular author with a large number of commits. These projects would easily fall under the umbrella of the right-skewed graphs if instead of having only one author with a large number of commits, they had multiple authors with a large number of commits. So in truth it seems that these graphs still demonstrate the same relationship as the right-skewed graph - there is still a small number of core contributors that make most of the commits and many contributors that make a few commits each.

A good example of the unimodal graph is the graph for https://gitub.com/pes-modding/sider5 project. However calling this graph and the others like it biomal is a bit disingenuous. The unimodal graphs are only the graphs for which there is only one author which makes them de-facto unimoal distributions since it's only a distribution of a single data point. In these projects there is a still a small number of core contributors that make most of the commits but in these specific projects there are no contributors that make a small number of commits. Perhaps in these cases it is because the project has not yet become large enough to get the attention of other mod developers that would want to contribute code into the mod (this can be said because from previously analysis it is known that the projects with only one author all have a total number of commits that is very small - less than 200).

So the overall information that can be taken from these graphs is that the contributions to an open source video game mod seem to follow a right-skewed distribution.

In [100]:
# now rather than looking at the distribution of commits looking at
# the percentage of commits will allow for normalizing the commit data
# across projects so overall information can be better created

# determine the percentage of commits created by the author with the most commits
# then determine what percentage of commits would be created by each author if
# each author made the same number of commits, i.e. the average commit percentage
# which is just number 100 percent divided by the number of authors
top_percent = []
average_percent = []
for project in commit_map:
    max_count = 0
    total_count = 0
    for author in commit_map[project]:
        if commit_map[project][author] > max_count:
            max_count = commit_map[project][author]
        total_count += commit_map[project][author]
    top_percent.append(max_count / total_count)
    average_percent.append(1 / len(commit_map[project].keys()))
    
plt.hist(top_percent, 20)
plt.gca().set_xlabel('Percent of commits')
plt.gca().set_ylabel('Number of top commiters')
plt.title('Distribution of percentage of commits made the top contributor to each project')

plt.figure()
plt.hist(average_percent, 20)
plt.gca().set_xlabel('Percent of commits')
plt.gca().set_ylabel('Number of projects')
plt.title('Distribution of average percentage of commits made by each contributor by project')
Out[100]:
Text(0.5,1,'Distribution of average percentage of commits made by each contributor by project')

The above graphs show two distrubtions: the first graph being the distribution of the percentage of the total number of commits in a project contributed by the one author with the largest number of commits, and the second graph being the distribution of the percentage of commits contributed on average by each author to the same projects. This allows for a comparison between the work done by the author with the largest number of commits and the average work done per commiter. This can be done with a two-sample KS test. Despite the two histograms above being categorical data, the underlying data is qualitative which means that the two-sample KS test can be used. The two-sample KS test determines if two distributions are statistically different.

In [117]:
result = ks_2samp(top_percent, average_percent)
print("p value for two-sample KS test is = " + str(result.pvalue))

p value for two-sample KS test is = 2.29723798395e-08

The p value given by the two-sample KS test is far smaller than any commonly used alpha value (0.05, 0.01, etc...) which means that it can confidently be said that the percentage of commits made by the top commiter is statistically different from the percentage of commits made by the average commiter to a project.

From this information, the next step is to compute the difference in percentage of commits between the top commiter and average commiter in order to determine the average amount that the top commiter overperforms the average commiter in order to get a good idea of just how much more these commiters contribute to the project.

In [122]:
delta_percent = []
for project in commit_map:
    max_count = 0
    total_count = 0
    for author in commit_map[project]:
        if commit_map[project][author] > max_count:
            max_count = commit_map[project][author]
        total_count += commit_map[project][author]
    top = max_count / total_count
    average = 1 / len(commit_map[project].keys())
    delta_percent.append(top - average)
    
plt.hist(top_percent, 20)
plt.gca().set_xlabel('Percent of commits more than the average commiter')
plt.gca().set_ylabel('Number of top commiters')
plt.title('Distribution of delta in percentage of commits made the top contributor more than the average commiter to each project')

series = pd.Series(delta_percent)
print("Five number summary for delta percents")
print(series.describe())

From the above analysis the mean percent delta is 32.8 percent and the median percent delta is 32.1% meaning that the top commiter to a project is on average making more than 30% more of the contributions to the project than the average commiter. Note that this does not mean that they are making 30% more commits to the project than the average commiter. It means that the percentage of total commits in the project made by the top commiter is 30% more than the average commiter. The difference between these two measures is that in a project with 1000 commits where the average commiter makes 100 commits (10% of the commits) the 30% average that has been computed above means that the top commiter would on average make 10% + 30% = 40% * 1000 = 400 commits to the project not 100 + 30% of 100 = 130 commits.

The importance of this information is that it defintely shows the importance of the top one commiter to the development of any open source modding project. Additionally, looking back at the earlier analysis that produced histograms of the number of commits for each project, it is clear that the other top commiters to the project (not only the one top commiter) are very important to the project development. This importance can be seen by noticing that if these contributors to the project had not contributed to the project the project would have at least 30% decrease in contributions.
